WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:02.811
Watch the two pilots
on the glide track.

2
00:00:02.811 --> 00:00:04.567
At first, both are still.

3
00:00:04.567 --> 00:00:06.113
Now watch their hands.

4
00:00:06.113 --> 00:00:10.188
Their palms press, and both
platforms begin to move apart.

5
00:00:10.188 --> 00:00:12.226
The motion is our first clue.

6
00:00:12.226 --> 00:00:14.615
Which two objects
are interacting?

7
00:00:14.615 --> 00:00:17.972
A force is a push or pull
during an interaction.

8
00:00:17.972 --> 00:00:20.908
The blue pilot pushes
on the orange pilot.

9
00:00:20.908 --> 00:00:25.244
At the same moment, the orange
pilot pushes on the blue pilot.

10
00:00:25.244 --> 00:00:29.440
One interaction produces two
forces, acting on two different

11
00:00:29.440 --> 00:00:29.999
objects.

12
00:00:29.999 --> 00:00:33.407
Follow each arrow to the
object receiving the push.

13
00:00:33.407 --> 00:00:36.414
Blue on orange belongs
with the orange pilot.

14
00:00:36.414 --> 00:00:39.287
Orange on blue belongs
with the blue pilot.

15
00:00:39.287 --> 00:00:42.761
The arrows are equal in
length and point in opposite

16
00:00:42.761 --> 00:00:43.496
directions.

17
00:00:43.496 --> 00:00:45.768
One interaction;
two force arrows.

18
00:00:48.768 --> 00:00:51.834
Compare the evidence
before and after contact.

19
00:00:51.834 --> 00:00:54.632
Before the push, both
platforms are still.

20
00:00:54.632 --> 00:00:56.498
Afterwards, they move apart.

21
00:00:56.498 --> 00:00:57.898
The change is motion.

22
00:00:57.898 --> 00:01:01.830
We do not see a force floating
through the air; we identify

23
00:01:01.830 --> 00:01:04.562
the interaction and
measure what changes.

24
00:01:04.562 --> 00:01:08.456
Here is an idea worth testing:
perhaps the push travels inside

25
00:01:08.456 --> 00:01:09.147
each pilot.

26
00:01:09.147 --> 00:01:10.341
Check the sequence.

27
00:01:10.341 --> 00:01:14.235
While their palms touch, the
contact-force arrows are present.

28
00:01:14.235 --> 00:01:17.376
When their hands separate,
those arrows disappear.

29
00:01:17.376 --> 00:01:21.145
The platforms keep gliding, but
that contact push has ended.

30
00:01:21.145 --> 00:01:23.452
Contact forces can push or pull.

31
00:01:23.452 --> 00:01:27.634
In the first bay, the robot's
padded hand pushes the cart.

32
00:01:27.634 --> 00:01:31.744
In the second, the robot pulls
the trolley through a taut

33
00:01:31.744 --> 00:01:32.176
cable.

34
00:01:32.176 --> 00:01:34.267
In both cases, name the pair.

35
00:01:34.267 --> 00:01:37.728
One object alone cannot
describe an interaction.

36
00:01:40.728 --> 00:01:43.562
Now focus on the gap
between the magnets.

37
00:01:43.562 --> 00:01:47.157
They do not touch, yet both
carts can begin to move.

38
00:01:47.157 --> 00:01:50.337
That is evidence of a
non-contact interaction.

39
00:01:50.337 --> 00:01:54.347
Gravity is another example:
Earth pulls objects towards it

40
00:01:54.347 --> 00:01:56.490
without making surface contact.

41
00:01:56.490 --> 00:01:59.568
Use two questions to
classify an interaction.

42
00:01:59.568 --> 00:02:02.167
First: which two
objects are involved?

43
00:02:02.167 --> 00:02:03.672
Second: do they touch?

44
00:02:03.672 --> 00:02:05.997
A robot hand on a
cart is contact.

45
00:02:05.997 --> 00:02:08.186
Magnet on magnet is non-contact.

46
00:02:08.186 --> 00:02:10.853
Earth pulling an
object is non-contact.

47
00:02:10.853 --> 00:02:14.273
Strength does not choose
the label; touching does.

48
00:02:14.273 --> 00:02:18.569
For a fair comparison, keep the
cart, track, and starting line

49
00:02:18.569 --> 00:02:19.192
the same.

50
00:02:19.192 --> 00:02:23.280
Change only the size of the
push, then measure the distance

51
00:02:23.280 --> 00:02:25.151
travelled in the same time.

52
00:02:25.151 --> 00:02:29.169
If several conditions change
together, the evidence cannot

53
00:02:29.169 --> 00:02:31.248
tell us which change mattered.

54
00:02:34.248 --> 00:02:35.653
Return to the pilots.

55
00:02:35.653 --> 00:02:39.668
Their platforms are still moving
after their hands separate.

56
00:02:39.668 --> 00:02:42.612
Does that mean a push
is stored inside them?

57
00:02:42.612 --> 00:02:42.813
No.

58
00:02:42.813 --> 00:02:46.560
The contact interaction
happened first and changed their

59
00:02:46.560 --> 00:02:47.029
motion.

60
00:02:47.029 --> 00:02:50.976
After contact ends, the new
motion can continue while other

61
00:02:50.976 --> 00:02:52.114
forces still act.

62
00:02:52.114 --> 00:02:55.006
Make a prediction before
the magnet trial runs.

63
00:02:55.006 --> 00:02:58.636
Which observations would support
a non-contact interaction?

64
00:02:58.636 --> 00:03:00.790
Take three quiet
seconds to decide.

65
00:03:00.790 --> 00:03:04.543
Now check: the gap remains
visible, both carts change motion,

66
00:03:04.543 --> 00:03:06.512
and no hand touches either cart.

67
00:03:06.512 --> 00:03:08.789
Those observations
support the claim.

68
00:03:08.789 --> 00:03:12.941
Use this physicist's routine
whenever you investigate a force.

69
00:03:12.941 --> 00:03:14.146
Name both objects.

70
00:03:14.146 --> 00:03:15.888
Decide whether they touch.

71
00:03:15.888 --> 00:03:18.566
Then use a change in
motion as evidence.

72
00:03:18.566 --> 00:03:22.116
A force is not hidden material
carried by one object.

73
00:03:22.116 --> 00:03:25.464
A force belongs to an
interaction between objects.

